name: Arpan s
review_text:
The Mysterious Invitation to Hawa Mahal

It was a chilly winter evening in Jaipur, and I was sitting in my cozy little apartment, sipping a cup of hot tea. Suddenly, I heard a knock on the door. I wasnt expecting anyone, so I was a bit surprised. I opened the door to find a mysterious figure cloaked in shadows. He handed me a small, intricately designed envelope with a wax seal bearing the emblem of Hawa Mahal.

Who are you? I asked, but the figure vanished into thin air before I could get an answer.

I was left standing there, holding the envelope and wondering what was going on. I carefully opened the seal and pulled out a small, ornate card with a message written in elegant calligraphy:

Meet me at Hawa Mahal at midnight. Come alone. The winds of the past await you.

I was both intrigued and terrified. Who could be behind this mysterious invitation, and what did they want from me? But my curiosity got the better of me, and I decided to take a chance.

As the clock struck midnight, I made my way to Hawa Mahal, my heart racing with anticipation. The palace was shrouded in darkness, except for a faint, flickering light emanating from the top floor. I entered the palace, my footsteps echoing off the stone walls.

As I climbed the stairs, the light grew brighter, and I saw a figure standing at the edge of the balcony. It was a woman with long, flowing hair and a white dress that billowed in the wind. She beckoned me to come closer.

Suddenly, the wind picked up, and the palaces famous lattice windows began to creak and groan. The woman raised her hands, and the wind died down. She turned to me and said, Welcome, traveler. I have been waiting for you. Tonight, I will reveal to you the secrets of Hawa Mahal, secrets that have been hidden for centuries.

As she spoke, the palace began to transform around me. The walls seemed to fade away, revealing a labyrinth of hidden passages and secret chambers. I followed the woman through the winding corridors, marveling at the intricate carvings and ornate frescoes.

We reached a hidden courtyard, where a group of musicians and dancers were waiting. The music began, and the woman took my hand, leading me into a whirlwind of color and sound. I felt like I was transported to a different era, one of opulence and grandeur.

As the night wore on, the woman revealed to me the stories of the royal women who had lived in Hawa Mahal, their struggles and triumphs, their secrets and scandals. I felt like I was living through history, experiencing the palace in a way that few others had.

As the first light of dawn began to creep over the horizon, the woman led me back to the balcony, where I had first met her. She smiled and said, Now you know the secrets of Hawa Mahal. Remember, the winds of the past are always whispering secrets to those who listen.

And with that, she vanished into thin air, leaving me standing alone on the balcony, feeling exhilarated and transformed. I knew that I would never forget this night, this magical journey through the secrets of Hawa Mahal.

name: Mahendra Pawar
review_text:
Hawa Mahal is a palace in Jaipur, India, built of pink sandstone and marble. It is a popular tourist attraction due to its unique architecture and intricate details.
The palace is located on Hawa Mahal Road, in the Badi Choupad area of Jaipur. It was built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh, and is one of the most recognizable landmarks in Jaipur.
The Hawa Mahal is a five-storey building with a honeycomb-like facade. It is designed to allow cool air to circulate through the palace, making it a comfortable place to stay even in the hot summer months. The palace is also home to a number of beautiful murals and sculptures.
The Hawa Mahal is open to the public from 9:00 AM to 4:30 PM every day. Tickets cost 20 for Indian citizens and 500 for foreign tourists.
Here are some additional details about the Hawa Mahal:
* It is a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
* It is one of the most photographed buildings in India.
* It is a popular location for weddings and other special events.
If you are visiting Jaipur, the Hawa Mahal is a must-see. It is a beautiful and unique building with a rich history.

name: Nevin Jose
review_text:
**Review for Hawa Mahal:**
Hawa Mahal, also known as the Palace of Winds, is a breathtaking architectural gem in Jaipur. Its stunning facade with 953 intricately carved windows is a visual treat. Designed to allow royal women to observe street festivities without being seen, the palace offers a glimpse into the rich history and culture of Rajasthan. Climbing up to the top provides magnificent views of the city and nearby landmarks. The craftsmanship and historical significance make it a must-visit for history buffs and architecture enthusiasts alike. A well-maintained heritage site, it truly captures the essence of Jaipurs royal past.

name: Akhtar Khatri
review_text:
The Hawa Mahal (meaning Palace of Winds) is one of the most iconic landmarks of Jaipur, India. Built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh, it was designed by the architect Lal Chand Ustad in the form of a crown, inspired by the shape of Lord Krishna's crown. The structure is made of pink sandstone and is an impressive example of Rajput architecture combined with elements of Mughal design.

The Hawa Mahal is particularly famous for its unique facade, which features 953 small windows, called jharokhas, decorated with intricate latticework. This design allowed royal women to observe street life without being seen, in line with the social customs of the time. The windows also helped to keep the palace cool, earning the building its name, as the cool breeze would flow through the latticework and provide ventilation, making it a comfortable retreat during the hot summers.

The palace has five stories and is not a full-fledged palace but more of a grand facade, with a central courtyard and rooms that are connected by narrow corridors. The Hawa Mahals design allows for a lot of light and air, making it stand out as a symbol of Rajput elegance and architectural ingenuity.

Today, the Hawa Mahal is a popular tourist attraction in Jaipur, offering a blend of history, culture, and architectural beauty, and is often photographed for its picturesque exterior. It is located near City Palace and Jantar Mantar, making it a key stop for visitors exploring Jaipurs rich heritage.

name: monika mishra
review_text:
My favourite place 
A Royal Welcome to Solo Travel: Hawa Mahal Jaipur
As a solo traveler embarking on my first trip, I was both excited and nervous about exploring the vibrant city of Jaipur. My first stop was the iconic Hawa Mahal, a stunning palace that exceeded my expectations in every way.

Awe-Inspiring Architecture

As I approached the palace, I was struck by its intricate architecture and delicate latticework. The Hawa Mahals unique design, with its 953 windows and ornate facade, is a testament to the ingenuity and craftsmanship of the Rajput era.

A Royal Experience

As a solo traveler, I was a bit apprehensive about navigating the palace on my own. However, the friendly and knowledgeable guides at Hawa Mahal put me at ease, sharing fascinating stories and anecdotes about the palaces history and significance.

Tips and Recommendations for Solo Travelers

- Arrive early to avoid the crowds and heat.
- Hire a guide to get the most out of your visit and learn about the palaces rich history.
- Be respectful of the palaces rules and regulations, as well as the local culture.
- Dont forget to take plenty of photos - the palaces intricate architecture and stunning views make for amazing Instagram shots!

Address: Hawa Mahal, Tripolia Bazar, Jaipur-302002

name: Dineesh C
review_text: Jaipur's Hawa Mahal, made of red and pink sandstone, is a breathtaking masterpiece of local artistry. From the top of the palace, you can enjoy a panoramic view of the city. And at night, the lights on the architecture create a magical ambiance that's simply awe-inspiring. If you're looking for a different perspective, there are two cafes opposite Hawa Mahal where you can watch the beauty of the palace bathed in the night lights .

name: Naved Kapoor
review_text:
I recently visited Hawa Mahal in Jaipur, and I must say, its an architectural marvel that left me spellbound! This 18th-century palace is a stunning example of Rajputana architecture, with its intricate latticework, ornate carvings, and majestic arches.

As I approached the palace, I was struck by its sheer scale and beauty. The facade of the palace is a riot of colors, with its pink and red sandstone walls gleaming in the sunlight. As I stepped inside, I was struck by the cool, airy interior, which is a testament to the ingenuity of the palaces designers.

One of the most striking features of Hawa Mahal is its unique lattice-like design, which allows the wind to circulate freely throughout the palace. This clever design feature not only keeps the palace cool but also provides stunning views of the surrounding city.

I spent hours exploring the palace, marveling at its intricate carvings, and learning about its rich history. The palace is a treasure trove of Rajasthani culture and heritage, and I felt privileged to have experienced it.

Overall, I highly recommend Hawa Mahal to anyone visiting Jaipur. Its a must-see attraction that will leave you awestruck and inspired.

Rating: 5/5 stars

name: Krishna Kunwar
review_text:
Hawa Mahal, Jaipur: A Detailed Review

Overview:
Hawa Mahal, also known as the Palace of Winds, is an iconic landmark of Jaipur. Built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh, this five-story structure is famous for its intricate latticework and unique honeycomb-like design. It was constructed to allow royal women to observe everyday life and festivals on the streets below without being seen, adhering to the purdah system of the time.

---

Key Highlights

1. Architecture and Design:

Made of red and pink sandstone, blending Mughal and Rajput architectural styles.

Features 953 small windows (jharokhas) with intricate latticework.

The facade resembles a beehive, symbolizing Lord Krishna's crown.

2. Cooling System:

The lattice design ensures excellent ventilation, keeping the palace cool even during scorching summers.

A brilliant example of sustainable architectural practices

name: Jai Ganesh K.B.
review_text:
Beautiful building that is supposed to be well ventilated all year round. The Mahal looks splendid from outside and there is not much to see on the inside. The most striking feature is its five-story structure, with a honeycomb or bee-hive pattern of windows, which were originally designed to allow cool air to circulate through the palace, earning it the name Palace of Winds (Hawa Mahal). The palace has 953 small windows or jharokhas, which are intricately designed with fine latticework, creating an illusion of a grand facade that looks like a giant crown. If you are short on time, best is to take a pic from outside but be ready to bear the huge number of people asking you to avail their photo services.

name: Ananthu A
review_text:
The night view of Hawa Mahal is very beautiful.

It is also very beautiful to see in the early morning and evening.

The lights in the city will be turned off at 12 midnight. All the shops will be closed. This place should be visited during this time.

There is a metro facility from the railway station to reach Hawa Mahal. The exit of Hawa Mahal is at Terminal One of the metro.

Also, shared taxis are available. Shared taxi drivers are very big scammers. Be careful and deal with them. Only travel after asking the price at the beginning. The cost of the shared taxi for two of us was 80 rupees (hawa mahal to railway station).

You should be careful during these hours as the heat will be extremely intense from 9 am to 4 pm.

The entry fee for Hawamahal can be obtained online or offline from there.

The interior of Hawamahal is very beautiful. Hawamahal is a historical place.
Its entire history is written within it.

Everyone should definitely visit.

A must-visit destination for history enthusiasts!

name: Gabriel B G de Oliveira Filho
Xyz FFM
review_text:
The Hawa Mahal, also known as the "Palace of Winds," is an architectural masterpiece and a must-visit landmark in Jaipur. Its stunning facade, with 953 intricately designed windows (Jharokhas), is a remarkable example of the blend of Rajput and Mughal architecture.

Highlights:
* Architecture: The intricate details and honeycomb-like structure make Hawa Mahal one of the most photogenic spots in Jaipur.
* History: Built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh, the palace allowed royal women to observe street life without being seen.
* Views: The top floors offer breathtaking views of Jaipur and the surrounding hills.

Tips:
* Visit early in the morning when the facade is beautifully illuminated by sunlight.
* Consider hiring a guide to better understand the historical and cultural significance.
* Don't miss exploring the interiors, which are simple yet elegant.

Room for Improvement:
The site could benefit from better signage and more information about its history, perhaps through plaques or audio guides.

Conclusion:
Hawa Mahal is a symbol of the grandeur and culture of Jaipur's past. A visit here is not just a glimpse into history but also a visual treat. A true highlight of Rajasthan!

name: Akash Joseph
review_text:
Hawa Mahal is an architectural gem in the heart of Jaipur, known for its stunning pink sandstone facade and intricate latticework. Its a must-visit for history enthusiasts, photographers, and anyone who appreciates unique architecture.

The iconic facade with its 953 windows is breathtaking and perfect for photography.
The purpose behind the design, allowing royal women to observe the streets while maintaining privacy, is fascinating. The views of Jaipur from the top of the palace are spectacular. Its location is convenient, surrounded by vibrant markets and other key attractions. The interiors are not as grand as the exterior and could use better maintenance.

The narrow staircases can feel cramped during busy hours. It gets very crowded, so visiting early in the morning is recommended.
Limited information available on-site--guided tours or audio guides would make the experience more enriching.

name: Megh Bale
review_text:
Very anticlimactic as this is the first place on your Jaipur city itinerary. Cannot visit it from inside and can only be viewed from the outside. This palace also known as the "palace of winds" was built by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh almost 250 years back. Has a great architectural design and an even richer history. It has a curved architecture that leans at an 87 degree angle, and a pyramidal shape which has helped it stay erect for centuries. The Hawa Mahal is dedicated to Lord Krishna. Unfortunately cant learn much from standing outside on a crowded street. Not really recommended.

name: Rohan Palkar
review_text:
Review of Hawa Mahal, Jaipur

Hawa Mahal, also known as the Palace of Winds, is an architectural marvel and one of Jaipur's most iconic landmarks. Its intricate design and historical significance make it a must-visit for anyone exploring the Pink City.

However, the location tends to be perpetually crowded, which can make the experience feel a bit overwhelming. Adding to the challenge is the lack of nearby parking facilities, so visitors should be prepared to walk a fair distance or rely on public transport.

Across from Hawa Mahal, you'll find several cafes offering a view of the palace, but be prepared for steep prices. While these cafes provide a picturesque setting, they may not be the best option if you're on a budget.

On a brighter note, the street markets around Hawa Mahal are a shopper's paradise, offering a wide variety of items at surprisingly affordable prices. From traditional Rajasthani textiles to handcrafted jewelry, it's a great place to pick up souvenirs without breaking the bank.

Overall, Hawa Mahal is a stunning site worth visiting, but some logistical challenges and pricing contrasts in the area may require a bit of planning to make the most of your trip.

name: Pankaj Khanna
review_text:
Hawa Mahal in Jaipur is an architectural marvel that left my wife and me in awe. Known as the Palace of Winds, this exquisite structure is a blend of Rajput and Mughal styles, with its stunning facade featuring 953 small windows, or jharokhas, which once allowed the royal ladies to observe life without being seen. The intricate latticework and delicate carvings are a testament to the artistry of the era, creating a captivating spectacle.

The ambiance of Hawa Mahal is simply enchanting, especially when you visit during sunset, as the warm glow of the setting sun bathes the palace in a golden hue. The view from the top is breathtaking, offering a panoramic sight of the city and the bustling streets below, making it feel like stepping back in time.

After exploring the palace, we highly recommend heading to the cafe opposite Hawa Mahal. A cup of tea while gazing at this timeless beauty is the perfect way to soak in the tranquility and magnificence of this landmark. It truly is a must-visit in Jaipur, offering not just a glimpse of history, but a serene and unforgettable experience.

name: prakash sreenivasa
review_text:
Superb building to watch in Jaipur.

Additional Information

Hawa Mahal (The Palace of Winds or The Palace of Breeze) is a palace in Jaipur, India approximately 300 kilometres from the capital city of Delhi.

Built from red and pink sandstone, the palace sits on the edge of the City Palace, Jaipur, and extends to the Zenana, or womens chambers.

The structure was built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh, the grandson of Maharaja Sawai Jai Singh, who was the founder of Jaipur.

It was designed by Lal Chand Ustad.

Its five-floor exterior is akin to honeycomb with its 953 small windows called Jharokhas decorated with intricate.

The palace is a five-storied pyramidal shaped building built in the form of Lord Krishna's crown as Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh was a devotee with the passion of Lord Krishna.

The architecture of the building insights us of the mixed culture of the Hindu Rajputs and Mughals also resembling a beautiful honeycomb of a beehive.

name: Tulika Sarkar
review_text:
The Palace of Whispers

Discover the enchanting Hawa Mahal, a 18th-century Rajput architectural marvel in Jaipur. This palace, built by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh, features a delicate latticework of intricately carved windows, allowing royal women to observe the outside world while remaining secluded.

Key Facts:

- Built in 1799
- 5-story palace made of red and pink sandstone
- 953 intricately carved windows
- UNESCO World Heritage Site

Travel Guidelines:

*Location:* Hawa Mahal Road, Badi Choupad, J.D.A. Market, Jaipur
*Timings:* 9:30 AM - 4:30 PM (April-September), 9:30 AM - 4:00 PM (October-March)
*Entry Fee:* 50 (Indians), 200 (Foreigners) *Best Time to Visit:* October to February (cool weather)
Its in the heart of the city so ppl interested at shopping can hop around and buy jaipuri and Rajasthani staffs.
Negotiation is a must.
Must try- local snacks( different types of kachori and lassi)
Giving photography is a must.

name: Singi
review_text:
Hawa Mahal in Jaipur is an architectural marvel that beautifully showcases Rajasthans rich heritage. Known as the Palace of Winds, its intricate honeycomb design and countless windows allow cool breezes to flow through, making it a perfect retreat even in the summer heat. The stunning facade, crafted from pink sandstone, is a sight to behold, especially during sunrise. Exploring the palace offers a glimpse into royal history and breathtaking views of the city from the top. A must-visit for anyone traveling to Jaipur, Hawa Mahal is a symbol of elegance and historical grandeur.

name: anjali kashyap
review_text:
Hawa Mahal, also known as the "Palace of Winds," is an architectural marvel in Jaipur and a must-visit for history and culture enthusiasts. The intricate latticework and unique five-story facade with its 953 small windows (jharokhas) are stunning examples of Rajput architecture. The design allows cool air to circulate naturally, making it a perfect retreat during Rajasthan's hot summers.

While the exterior is breathtaking, the interiors are relatively simple, so the highlight is definitely the view from the top, which offers a panoramic glimpse of Jaipur's bustling streets. However, the site can get crowded, and the upkeep could be better in some areas. Overall, it's a fascinating monument that gives you a glimpse into India's royal past.

name: Vaibhav Seth
review_text:
Hawa Mahal is a beautiful structure with stunning architecture, but my experience was far from pleasant. The crowds were overwhelming, making it difficult to enjoy the intricate details of the palace. The staff seemed uninterested in helping visitors, which added to the frustration. The area was also quite dirty, detracting from the overall experience.

If you're looking for a peaceful visit to appreciate the history and beauty of Hawa Mahal, I would recommend skipping it. Instead, consider exploring other less crowded attractions in Jaipur. Overall, I would not recommend this place to anyone seeking a memorable experience.

Weekday

name: ravi maharshi
review_text:
It is a very vibrant and magnificent building. It is a 5 storey building and there are lots of windows inside. Walk from one floor to the second, third, fourth and fifth floor and enjoy the lots of windows.

Its name Hawa Mahal is right because after going here you feel a lot of air. There are many types of windows here, some are small, some are big, some will be even bigger. A lot of glass work has also been done inside and it looks fantastic.

There is a fountain in the middle of Hawa Mahal, its view is also wonderful. There are many photo shoot places in Hawa Mahal where you will enjoy.

After reaching the top, the view of Jaipur feels even more amazing. Come with your family and friends and enjoy.

name: Ashutosh Tiwari
review_text:
I recently visited Hawa Mahal, and it was a great experience. The palace looks amazing from the outside with its unique windows and pink color. Inside, the narrow stairs and passages were interesting to explore.

The best part for me was the cool breeze coming through the small windows and the view from the top. You can see a lot of the city from there, and it feels peaceful.

The entry was easy and less crowd makes easy to see the beauty of the mahal

name: Varnit Gupta
review_text:
Hawa Mahal, also known as the Palace of Winds, is an architectural marvel that truly lives up to its reputation. The intricate latticework on the facade and the stunning pink sandstone design are breathtaking and offer a glimpse into the grandeur of Jaipurs royal heritage.

The palace is perfect for history enthusiasts and photographers alike. The view from the top is spectacular, giving a birds-eye view of the bustling city and nearby attractions. The gentle breeze flowing through the jharokhas (windows) is a refreshing reminder of why it's called the Palace of Winds.

That said, the site could be better maintained in certain areas, and information for tourists could be more comprehensive. A little more effort to enhance the visitor experience would make it flawless.

Overall, Hawa Mahal is a must-visit in Jaipur--a four-star experience for its beauty, charm, and cultural significance.
Visited on
Weekend

name: vedant koli
review_text:
The Hawa Mahal, also known as the Palace of Winds, is an architectural marvel that truly captures the grandeur of Jaipurs royal heritage. Built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh, this iconic pink sandstone palace stands as a testament to the rich Rajputana culture and artistry.

*Design and Architecture

The most striking feature of the Hawa Mahal is its intricate facade with 953 small windows, or jharokhas, adorned with delicate latticework. These windows were designed to allow royal women to observe street festivals and daily life without being seen, in adherence to the purdah system. The structure resembles a honeycomb and glows beautifully when sunlight hits it, especially during early mornings.

*Experience

Walking through the palace, you feel transported back in time. The cool breeze flowing through the jharokhas provides a unique experience, which justifies its name. The narrow corridors and steep ramps might be a bit challenging, but they add to the charm. The panoramic view of Jaipur from the top is breathtaking, offering sights of bustling markets and nearby landmarks.
Visited on
Weekend

name: Ravi jharoliya
review_text:
According to Rajasthan Tourism, Hawa Mahal in Jaipur is considered one of the major attractions of the city. This five-storey building looks like a beehive and has innumerable windows and vents, due to which air always keeps flowing inside the palace. Because of this cave, it has been named Hawa Mahal.13 June 2024
The Hawa Mahal is dedicated to Lord Krishna. It is said that the shape of the building resembles the crown of Krishna. More than a palace, the Hawa Mahal is also a cultural and architectural marvel that reflects a truly harmonious amalgamation of the Hindu Rajput and Islamic Mughal architectural styles.

name: Vipin Bansal
review_text:
A beautiful structure, can be seen in day and night time also. There is a parking problem and numerous small vendors selling snacks and crafted things.

Hawa Mahal, the Palace of Winds, is a stunning five-story architectural marvel in Jaipur. Built in 1799, its intricate lattice windows allow cool breezes to flow through. Offering a glimpse into royal life, it's a must-visit for its unique design, historical significance, and panoramic views of the city.

History- Hawa Mahal, built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh, is an iconic symbol of Jaipur's royal heritage. Designed by architect Lal Chand Ustad in red and pink sandstone, it features 953 intricate windows. The palace allowed royal women to observe city life while maintaining their privacy, reflecting Rajput traditions.

name: Sukumar Ghosh
review_text: located in Jaipur Rajasthan Hawa Mahal, built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh, ,was designed by Lalchand ustad and is also Known as the Palace of Winds, . The palace has 953 small windows to allow royal women to observe street festivities without being seen adhering to purdah customs. and also the honeycomb design windows allowed cool air to pass through, creating natural ventilation in the scorching desert heat.

name: Binu A.S
review_text:
Location:
Hawa Mahal is situated in Jaipur, Rajasthan, India, on the main road of Badi Chaupad, near the City Palace.

Established:
The Hawa Mahal was built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh, the ruler of Jaipur at the time. The palace was designed by architect Lal Chand Usta, who combined the Rajput and Mughal architectural styles. Its design was intended to reflect the grandeur of Jaipur while catering to the needs of the royal women.

Original Story and Purpose:
The primary purpose behind the construction of Hawa Mahal was to enable the royal women to observe the life and activities of the city without being seen by the public. Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh was a devout follower of Lord Krishna, and it is said that he was inspired by the intricate latticework seen in the temples of Vrindavan, where Lord Krishna is believed to have spent his childhood. The palace was constructed with the idea of creating a space where the women could watch street festivals, processions, and the bustling city life below, all while maintaining their privacy and seclusion, a practice typical for royal women during that era.

The palace's five-story structure is designed with 953 small windows, or jharokhas, and is adorned with beautiful latticework. These windows were specifically built to allow cool air to flow through the palace, keeping it cool in the heat of the desert. This ventilation system led to the name Hawa Mahal or Palace of Winds. The architectural design of the Hawa Mahal is also a blend of Rajput and Mughal styles, with arches, domes, and intricate carvings.

Historical Significance:
The Hawa Mahal is not just a building but an embodiment of the lifestyle of the royal women during the 18th century. It symbolizes the need for privacy and the royal family's desire to observe and participate in the cultural and social life of the city without breaking the strict codes of conduct for women at the time.

The structure, with its stunning facade and artistic beauty, was not only a private space but also an architectural symbol of the grandeur of Jaipurs royal family. It forms a significant part of the City Palace complex and was an essential element of the palaces social life, serving as a place for relaxation and a venue to watch the activities in the city.

Modern-Day Significance:
Hawa Mahal is one of Jaipurs most iconic landmarks and a must-visit tourist destination. Although it no longer serves as a royal residence, it remains a representation of Jaipurs rich architectural heritage and royal lifestyle. The palace has been well-preserved and is now a museum, attracting thousands of visitors annually who come to admire its unique structure and take in the panoramic views of Jaipur from its upper floors.

The Hawa Mahal continues to be a testament to the ingenuity and elegance of Rajput architecture, blending history, culture, and art in one magnificent structure.

name: sina nosrati
review_text:
Hawa Mahal, or the Palace of Winds, is a beautiful and iconic structure in Jaipur, known for its unique facade of over 900 intricately designed windows, or jharokhas. Built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh, this five-story palace was originally created to allow royal ladies to observe the street life and festivals of Jaipur without being seen by the public. The architecture is inspired by the shape of Lord Krishna's crown, and its pink and red sandstone walls fit right into Jaipurs nickname as the Pink City.

While the exterior is stunning and certainly worth admiring, I found that the interior was not as impressive as the facade suggests. It's mostly empty inside, with a few rooms and narrow corridors but not much historical detail or art to explore. The panoramic view of Jaipur from the top is nice, but it doesn't add much to the overall experience if you're expecting an elaborate palace. I'd recommend stopping by to see the unique architecture from the outside but managing expectations about the interior, as it's rather plain compared to other historic sites in Jaipur.

name: Nethra R Gowda
review_text:
We traveled from Bangalore, Karnataka, to Jaipur on 02 November 2024, hoping to immerse ourselves in the city's incredible history and culture. Unfortunately, our experience was overshadowed by the conduct of local tourist guides.

The guides we encountered seemed more focused on earning commissions than on genuinely guiding visitors. Instead of offering insights or engaging stories, they directed us to specific shops where they evidently had commission arrangements. Worse, they often left us at these shops without informing us and seemed more interested in the shopkeepers' benefits than in providing a meaningful experience for tourists.

The experience at Hawa Mahal was particularly troubling. Across from the monument, shopkeepers were charging extra fees just for taking photos from ideal viewpoints--spaces that should be freely accessible to all. Their behavior was rude and disrespectful, and hearing foreign tourists openly complain about Indian tourism in response was disappointing and painful for us as Indian visitors.

Jaipur and Rajasthan have so much beauty and cultural richness to offer, but these exploitative practices are harming the tourism experience.

I urge @RajasthanTourism and @DiyaKumari, the Deputy Chief Minister, to address these issues. Raising the standards for local guides, protecting tourists' interests, and preventing such exploitative behaviors would help ensure that everyone, both domestic and international visitors, can fully enjoy and appreciate what Rajasthan has to offer.

Customer Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh
technical details
Structural System Red and Pink Sandstone
planning and construction
Architect Lal Chand Ustad

Hawamahal
Hawa Mahal is a royal palace in Jaipur, the capital of the Indian state of Rajasthan. It was built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh near the metro station at Rajasthan Jaipur Badi Chaupar and was designed by architect Lal Chand Ustad like a rajmukut. Its unique five-storey building, which is only one and a half feet wide at the top, looks like a beehive when seen from outside, which has 953 very beautiful and attractive small latticed windows, which are called Jharokhas. The basic idea behind making these windows latticed was that without anyone noticing, the women of the royal family, who strictly followed the Purda Pratha, could observe the ceremonies and activities of daily life happening in the corridors on the streets below the palace through these windows. Can do. Apart from this, due to the Venturi effect, cool air always comes inside the palace through these intricately structured lattice windows, due to which the palace always remains air-conditioned even in the scorching heat.

Built of lime, red and pink sandstone, this palace is located on the main road in the heart of the commercial center of Jaipur. It is part of the City Palace and extends up to the Zenana Room or Ladies Room. Seeing it shining in the golden light of the sun early in the morning gives a unique feeling.

name: Hansraj Jhajhriya
review_text:
1. **Architectural Marvel**: Hawa Mahal is a stunning example of Rajput architecture. The intricate latticework and unique facade make it a photographers dream!

2. **Cultural Experience**: Visiting Hawa Mahal felt like stepping back in time. The history and stories associated with this palace are fascinating.

3. **Scenic Views**: The views from the top of Hawa Mahal are breathtaking! You can see the bustling streets of Jaipur and the beautiful cityscape.

4. **Great Location**: Situated in the heart of Jaipur, Hawa Mahal is easily accessible and makes for a perfect day trip combined with other nearby attractions.

5. **Family-Friendly**: A wonderful place to take the family! The kids loved exploring the various windows and learning about the history.

6. **Guided Tours**: The guided tours offer insightful information about the significance of Hawa Mahal. Our guide was knowledgeable and engaging!

Feel free to modify these to suit your needs!

name: Darshan Desai
review_text:
The Hawa Mahal, or Palace of Winds, is an architectural marvel in Jaipur. Its intricate facade, resembling a honeycomb, is adorned with numerous tiny windows called jharokhas. These jharokhas allowed the royal ladies to observe the bustling streets below without being seen.
The palaces unique design offers excellent ventilation, keeping the interiors cool even during the hot Rajasthan summers. Climbing to the top offers panoramic views of the Pink City. The Hawa Mahal is a testament to the ingenuity and artistry of the Rajput era, making it a must-visit for history and architecture enthusiasts.

name: Pratap Hari Singh
review_text:
Hawa Mahal known as "Palace of Winds" is one of the finest architecture in Jaipur, Rajasthan. Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh had built this palace in 1799. Hawa Mahal is considered unique because it has many small windows and balconies that look like a honeycomb.

The structure was built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh, grandson of Maharaja Sawai Jai Singh, the founder of Jhunjhunu city in Rajasthan state. He was so inspired by the unique structure of Khetri Mahal that he built this grand and historical palace.

It was designed by Lal Chand Ustad. Its five-storey outer building is honeycomb-like, with 953 small windows called Jharokhas decorated with intricate lattice work. The original purpose of the latticed design was to allow royal women to observe everyday life and festivals celebrated on the street below without being seen. This architectural feature also allowed cool air to pass through through the Venturi effect, making the entire area more pleasant during high temperatures in summer. Many people look at Hawa Mahal from the street view and think that this is the front part of the palace, but it is the back part.

In 2006, after a gap of 50 years, renovation work was started on the palace to give the monument a new look, with an estimated cost of Rs 4.568 million. The corporate sector helped preserve the historical monuments of Jaipur and the Unit Trust of India has adopted Hawa Mahal to maintain it. The palace is an extended part of a huge complex. Stone carved screens, small windows and arched ceilings are some of the features of this popular tourist destination. The monument also has delicately hanging cornices.

name: Chary Kasoju
review_text:
A Breathtaking Glimpse into Jaipurs Past: The Hawa Mahal

The Hawa Mahal, a towering five-story facade of pink sandstone, is a must-see landmark in Jaipur.

Our recent visit left us in awe of the exquisite architecture and overall elegance of the design. The Hawa Mahals most notable feature is its honeycomb-like structure, which is studded with hundreds of tiny windows that allow for a constant flow of cool air, thus the name Palace of the Winds. This clever design was designed to provide privacy for the royal women, allowing them to see the bustling streets below without being noticed.

As we wandered through the palaces small hallways and gardens, we were intrigued by the elaborate carvings and beautiful artwork that covered every surface. The sunlight streaming through the windows produced a beautiful dance of light and shadow, adding to the Hawa Mahals overall appeal.

A visit to the Hawa Mahal is not complete without climbing to the top floor for a panoramic view of Jaipurs bustling Old City. The vibrant colors and chaotic energy of the city below provide a stark contrast to the serene and peaceful atmosphere within the palace.

If youre planning a trip to Jaipur, the Hawa Mahal is an absolute must-visit. Its a testament to the architectural ingenuity and cultural richness of Rajasthan. Timings are 9AM to 6:30PM, better to visit in the daytime.
Visited on
Weekday

This place is managed by Govt of Rajasthan. Buying a ticket is a cumbersome process. It should be made easier.
However the monument is majestic. Offers a great view of Pink City which is now a World Heritage Site of UNESCO.
Hawa Mahal means windy palace. It was built by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh in 1799. This palace has 953 small windows that offers Ventury effect. The palace design is based on Khetri Mahal located in Neem Ka Thana town.

name: Utkarsh nolastname
review_text:
Hawa Mahal is a highly photographed landmark in the city of Jaipur, located in the Badi Chaupad area of the city. If you are familiar with the monument only through photographs, you will find it small compared to the notion of its size you would have formed. There was a crowd trying to capture the building just outside it. It is difficult to capture in a single frame unless you cross the road in front of it or at least try to take a snap standing at the median.
The traffic is heavy and one needs to be careful of the vehicles zipping by. Across the road from Hawa Mahal are small shops selling beautiful handicrafts and clothes. Be ready to bargain down to 50-60 percent of the price first quoted at these shops.

name: Aniket Sinha
review_text:
Hawa Mahal, also known as the Palace of Winds, is a stunning five-story building located in Jaipur, Rajasthan, India. Built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh, it is a unique example of Rajput architecture, combining elements of both Rajput and Mughal styles.
Here are some key features of Hawa Mahal:
* Honeycomb Facade: The most striking feature of Hawa Mahal is its intricate facade, which resembles a honeycomb with numerous small windows known as jharokhas. These windows are beautifully designed with latticework and are arranged in a symmetrical pattern.
* Ventilation: The name Hawa Mahal translates to Palace of Winds, and it was designed to provide ventilation and cooling during the hot summer months in Rajasthan. The numerous jharokhas allow for a constant breeze to flow through the palace, keeping it cool and comfortable.
* Royal Womens Quarters: Hawa Mahal was originally built as a viewing screen for the royal women, who were required to observe purdah (seclusion) and could not be seen by men outside the palace. The jharokhas allowed them to watch the bustling streets and festivals without being seen.
* Architectural Marvel: Hawa Mahal is considered a masterpiece of Rajput architecture, showcasing the skill and craftsmanship of its builders. It is a testament to the rich cultural heritage of Rajasthan and is a popular tourist attraction.
Here are some additional facts about Hawa Mahal:
* It is the tallest building in the world built without a foundation.
* The main entrance is located at the rear of the building, and visitors can climb ramps to reach the upper floors.
* Hawa Mahal is a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
If youre planning a trip to Jaipur, Hawa Mahal is a must-see attraction. Its unique architecture, historical significance, and stunning beauty make it a truly unforgettable experience.

name: Poonam Chandel
review_text:
Hawa Mahal - An Architectural Marvel of Jaipur!

Hawa Mahal, also known as the Palace of Winds, is one of the most iconic landmarks in Jaipur and an absolute must-visit. The stunning five-story structure, with its honeycomb-like facade featuring 953 small windows or jharokhas, is a breathtaking example of Rajput architecture. It was built for the royal women to observe city life without being seen, and the intricate lattice work on the windows allows a cool breeze to flow through, giving the palace its name.

The palace is not just a visual treat from the outside but also offers a fascinating experience inside. As you walk through the narrow corridors and climb up the various levels, you get amazing views of the bustling streets of Jaipur and the Jantar Mantar from the top. The architecture is unique, with a blend of red and pink sandstone, and the detailed craftsmanship is a true reflection of the rich cultural heritage of Rajasthan.

One of the key highlights is the beautiful play of light and shadow inside the palace, especially in the early morning when the sunlight streams through the jharokhas, creating a magical atmosphere.

However, the interior space of Hawa Mahal is relatively small compared to its grand exterior, and there isn't much detailed signage to explain the history, so hiring a guide or using an audio guide is recommended for a deeper understanding. Also, due to its popularity, it can get crowded, particularly in the afternoons, so visiting in the early morning or late afternoon is ideal for a more peaceful experience.

Overall, Hawa Mahal is a magnificent structure that encapsulates the essence of Jaipur's royal history and architectural brilliance. It's not just a monument, but a symbol of the city itself!

name: yash verma
review_text:
Hawa Mahal, also known as the "Palace of Winds," is a must-visit destination in Jaipur! The architecture is absolutely stunning, with its iconic honeycomb facade featuring 953 small windows, or "jharokhas," which allowed royal ladies to observe street festivals while remaining unseen. The intricate latticework and vibrant pink sandstone make it a photographer's dream.

Once inside, you'll be amazed by the cool breeze that flows through the palace, even on a hot day, thanks to its unique design. The views from the upper floors offer a panoramic glimpse of the bustling city below and the majestic Aravalli hills in the distance.

The palace doesn't take too long to explore, so it's perfect for a quick yet enriching visit. There's also a small museum that provides insights into the history and significance of this architectural marvel.

For those looking to capture some Instagrammable photos, I highly recommend visiting the cafes located directly across from Hawa Mahal. These spots offer the perfect vantage point to capture the stunning facade from a distance, with the palace providing a breathtaking backdrop to your pictures. Plus, you can enjoy a cup of coffee or a snack while soaking in the view.

name: ABHISHEK BISHNOI
review_text:
Hawa Mahal, also known as the Palace of Winds, is one of the most iconic landmarks in Jaipur. Visitors consistently praise its stunning architecture, featuring 953 small windows (or jharokhas) that allow cool air to flow through, creating a pleasant breeze even during the hot summer months. The design, built in 1799, enabled royal women to observe street festivals while remaining hidden due to the purdah system.

Reviews on platforms like Google Maps highlight the palaces beauty, especially from the outside, with its unique pink sandstone facade. Many visitors recommend visiting early in the morning to avoid crowds and enjoy the soft sunlight reflecting off the palace. While the interior can feel a bit underwhelming compared to the facade, climbing to the higher levels offers nice views of Jaipur's bustling streets and nearby landmarks[(6)] [(7)] .

Additionally, many recommend grabbing a drink at one of the rooftop cafes across the street, which provide excellent views of the palace. Keep in mind, it's best to visit during cooler parts of the day, as there isnt much shade inside[(6)] .

name: Andrew Goh
review_text:
Nestled in the heart of Jaipurs Pink City at Badi Choupad, Hawa Mahal is a sight that immediately grabs your attention. Built in 1799, this stunning palace has 953 small, intricately designed windows on its facade. The honeycomb structure allows the breeze to flow through, making it a perfect escape from the heat during summer. What's fascinating is that Hawa Mahal wasn't just built for its beauty--it was designed as an extension of the nearby City Palace.

Sawai Pratap Singh, the Kachhwaha Rajput ruler and grandson of Maharaja Sawai Jai Singh, commissioned the palace in 1799. During that time, the Purdah system was strictly followed, meaning royal women were kept out of public view. Hawa Mahal was built so that the women could discreetly observe street life and royal processions below without being seen--a clever and thoughtful architectural solution for the time.

Today, Hawa Mahal sits along a bustling street, and the best way to truly take in its beauty is by standing across the road for a perfect photo opportunity. There's no entrance fee, and while the area can get busy, it's definitely a must-see and a lovely spot to snap some memorable pictures of this iconic piece of Jaipur's history.

name: Asif Hamzza
review_text:
### Hawa Mahal, Jaipur: A Captivating Experience

Hawa Mahal, or the Palace of Winds, is a prominent tourist attraction in Jaipur, renowned for its unique architecture and historical significance. Built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Jai Singh II, it was designed to allow royal women to observe the streets without being seen.

#### Architectural Marvel
The palace features 953 small windows, known as jharokhas, which provide ventilation and keep the interiors cool. Its design is a beautiful blend of Rajput and Mughal styles, making it a stunning sight.

#### Visitor Experience
Exploring the interiors of Hawa Mahal is a delightful experience. Each viewpoint offers a different perspective, with breathtaking views of Jaipur. Standing on the terrace, you can admire the cityscape, adding to the charm of the visit.

#### Facilities
Visitor amenities are well-maintained, including audio guides and special tour options that provide insights into the palace's history and significance.

#### Recommendation
If youre visiting Jaipur, Hawa Mahal is a must-see. Its beauty and history will make your trip unforgettable, leaving you enchanted by its elegance and tranquility.

name: Saurabh Bharat
review_text:
Hawa Mahal, also known as the Wind Palace, is a famous historical building located in Jaipur, Rajasthan. It was constructed by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh in 1799. It was built specifically for Rajput royal women so that they could observe the daily life and festivities of the city without being seen in public. The architecture of the palace is unique, being a blend of Rajput and Mughal styles.

Hawa Mahal is a five-storey building and its structure is like a beehive, which has 953 small windows. Due to these windows, cool air always flows in the palace, due to which it got the name Hawa Mahal. Built of red and pink sandstone, this palace looks different from other buildings of Jaipur and is also considered the symbol of the Pink City.

The main purpose of the palace was to allow women to enjoy the outside world while remaining behind the scenes. These windows allowed women to observe city events without being seen. Additionally, the Hawa Mahal had natural air conditioning, which kept it cool even in the heat of Rajasthan.

Today, Hawa Mahal is a major tourist destination, where thousands of tourists come every year to see its amazing architecture and history. There is also a museum inside it, in which objects related to Rajput art and culture are displayed. Hawa Mahal, due to its unique design and cultural significance, holds an important place in the heritage of Rajasthan.

review_text:
Hawa Mahal, located in Jaipur, Rajasthan, is an iconic palace known for its unique architecture and historical significance. Built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh, it is part of the City Palace complex. The palace is made of red and pink sandstone and is famous for its 953 small windows, or jharokhas, designed to allow royal ladies to observe street life without being seen, following the purdah system.

The structure resembles a honeycomb and offers a cool breeze through its many windows, which is why it is called the Palace of Winds (Hawa Mahal). It stands five stories tall and is a blend of Rajput and Mughal architectural styles.

The palace is made of red and pink sandstone and has 953 small windows or jharokas, which royal women used to watch outside activities while following the purdah ritual. Its structure resembles a beehive and its windows. Cold air comes from here, hence it is called Hawa Mahal. The palace is five storeys high and is a blend of Rajput and Mughal architectural styles.

The architecture is a stunning example of the grandeur of old construction, with its intricate windows and arches that truly capture the essence of Rajasthani heritage. The Diwan-e-Khas is particularly beautiful, offering a glimpse into the luxurious life of the royals.

One of the highlights of the visit is the student discount on ticket prices, making it more accessible for those pursuing their studies. I went on a weekday, and it was a peaceful and relaxing experience, with fewer crowds, allowing me to soak in the beauty of the monument without the hustle.

That being said, while the overall experience was fantastic, the palace could benefit from a bit more maintenance in certain areas. Some parts of the structure and facilities seem to have aged and could use restoration work to preserve their charm for future visitors. There is puppet show inside mahal.

Overall, Hawa Mahal is a must-visit for anyone in Jaipur, offering a mix of history, beauty, and cultural significance. If you want a peaceful visit, I recommend going during the weekdays.

name: Sandeep kumar
review_text: Hawa Mahal, the Palace of the Winds, is a breathtaking architectural marvel in Jaipur. This 18th-century monument is a must-see, famous for its magnificent pink sandstone facade and intricate lattice work. The unique design of the palace, which has 953 windows, is a mesmerizing display of light and shadow. I was impressed by the sheer scale and beauty of the architecture. The interior chambers, though small, offer a glimpse into the lives of the royal women who once lived in the palace. The views of the surrounding city from the upper floors are spectacular. The history and cultural significance of the palace is evident, and the surrounding gardens and courtyard add to the tranquil atmosphere. Hawa Mahal is an iconic symbol of Jaipurs rich heritage and a testament to the architectural brilliance of the city.

name: sadarulla khan
review_text:
The Hawa Mahal, or Palace of Winds, is a five-story building in Jaipur, India. It is known for its unique architecture, which features hundreds of small windows called jharokhas. These windows were designed to allow women of the royal family to observe the life outside the palace without being seen themselves. The building is also notable for its intricate carvings and colorful facade.
Here are some key points about the Hawa Mahal:
* Unique architecture: The building is famous for its hundreds of small windows called jharokhas that allow for ventilation and privacy.
* Historical significance: It was built for the women of the royal family to observe the life outside the palace without being seen.
* Intricate carvings and colorful facade: The building is adorned with intricate carvings and colorful designs.
* Popular tourist attraction: The Hawa Mahal is a popular tourist destination in Jaipur.

name: sanjay singh
review_text:
Hawa Mahal is an architectural marvel that should not be missed when visiting Jaipur! However, I recommend visiting late at night when its less crowded, allowing you to fully appreciate its beauty and intricate details without the daytime rush. The illuminated palace at night gives a magical vibe, making it the perfect time for a peaceful visit and great photo opportunities. During the day, it can get quite busy, so plan accordingly for the best experience!

name: Aryan Singh
review_text:
Hawa Mahal, also known as the Palace of Winds, stands as a breathtaking example of Rajput architecture in Jaipur, India. Built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh, this iconic structure is renowned for its stunning facade, which resembles a honeycomb or a screen of a beehive. The palace features 953 small windows or jharokhas,

Today, Hawa Mahal remains a symbol of Jaipurs rich cultural heritage and architectural innovation. It draws visitors from around the world, eager to experience its historical charm and remarkable design, affirming its status as one of Indias most celebrated landmarks.
Hawa Mahal, or the Palace of Winds, is a dazzling masterpiece of architectural elegance. This stunning structure, with its striking facade of delicate, honeycomb-like windows, captivates with an intricate lattice of red and pink sandstone. Its tiered design, resembling a grand screen, creates a mesmerizing visual effect as the sunlight dances through the ornate jharokhas, casting a captivating interplay of light and shadow.
The palaces facade is a symphony of geometric patterns and floral motifs, all meticulously crafted to enhance its beauty and function. The delicate, filigree-like screens not only offer aesthetic pleasure but also provide a cooling breeze, a necessity in the hot Rajasthan climate. From every angle, Hawa Mahal exudes a timeless grace and splendor.
As visitors gaze up at its intricate balconies and detailed carvings, the sheer artistry and grandeur of the palace become apparent. Each window offers a glimpse into a bygone era of royal opulence, blending function with sublime beauty. Hawa Mahal stands as a testament to the ingenuity and artistic vision of its creators, enchanting all who behold its remarkable facade.

name: h v
review_text:
Perched majestically in the heart of the bustling city, the Hawa Mahal stands as a testament to architectural brilliance and captivating allure. True to its name, which translates to Palace of Winds, this iconic structure offers a perpetual breeze that gracefully sweeps through its intricately designed facades. Despite its popularity, one does not feel suffocated within its walls, as the gentle currents of air imbue the atmosphere with a sense of tranquility.

With its mesmerizing presence, the Hawa Mahal emerges as an oasis of beauty amidst the vibrant chaos of the cityscape. Ascending to its pinnacle unveils a breathtaking panorama that leaves visitors spellbound. The view from the top is nothing short of a sensory feast, a symphony of colors, sights, and sounds that enthralls the beholder.

Throughout the year, the Hawa Mahal remains a magnet for tourists, drawing in crowds who seek to witness its ethereal grandeur. To gain access, a nominal ticket priced at 50/- unlocks the gateway to this architectural marvel. Visitors are encouraged to capture the enchantment with their cameras and mobile devices, ensuring that memories of this captivating experience can be treasured forever.

However, during peak periods, the Hawa Mahal can become crowded, necessitating vigilance in safeguarding personal belongings. Additionally, it is advisable to seize photographic opportunities promptly, as the surging throngs may limit the ability to capture numerous snapshots.

A visit to the Hawa Mahal is an absolute must, for it offers more than just aesthetic gratification. The ingenious design of the structure facilitates a continuous flow of air from all directions, ensuring a pleasantly cool ambiance that transcends the boundaries of seasons.

In essence, the Hawa Mahal stands as an architectural marvel, an enchanting oasis amidst the urban hustle and bustle. Its delicate beauty, ever-present breeze, and timeless allure combine to create an extraordinary experience that is etched indelibly in the minds and hearts of all who wander through its splendid halls.

name: sandeep jind
review_text:
Hawa Mahal, the Palace of Winds, is a breathtaking architectural marvel in Jaipur. This 18th-century monument is a must-visit attraction, renowned for its stunning pink sandstone facade and intricate latticework. The palaces unique design, featuring 953 windows, allows for a mesmerizing play of light and shadow.

As I explored the palace, I was struck by the sheer scale and beauty of the architecture. The interior chambers, though small, offer a glimpse into the lives of the royal women who once inhabited the palace. The views of the surrounding city from the top floors are simply spectacular.

The palaces history and cultural significance are palpable, and the surrounding gardens and courtyards add to the tranquil ambiance. The Hawa Mahal is an iconic symbol of Jaipurs rich heritage and a testament to the citys architectural prowess.

_Pros:_ Breathtaking architecture, stunning views, rich history, tranquil ambiance.

_Cons:_ Crowded during peak hours, limited access to certain areas, no guided tours.

name: Harish Siyag
review_text:
I had the privilege of visiting the breathtaking Hawa Mahal in Jaipur, and I must say, its an architectural marvel that exceeded my expectations! This 18th-century palace is a masterpiece of Rajput engineering, with its intricate latticework, ornate carvings, and stunning pink sandstone facade.

As I stepped inside, I was struck by the sheer scale and grandeur of the palaces 953 windows, which provide a fascinating glimpse into the lives of the royal women who once lived here. The cool breeze that wafts through the palaces corridors, a result of its ingenious design, is a welcome respite from the desert heat.

The views from the top are simply spectacular, offering a panoramic vista of the citys bustling streets and surrounding landscape. The palaces rich history and cultural significance are palpable, making for a deeply immersive and enriching experience.

Overall, Hawa Mahal is an absolute must-visit attraction in Jaipur, and I highly recommend it to anyone interested in history, architecture, or simply experiencing the beauty of Indias cultural heritage.

name: Massimo Grassi
review_text:
The Palazzo dei Venti is beautiful. Built to allow the wives of the royal family to be able to see the street without being seen. I recommend not just stopping to take a photograph from the outside, but going past it, and paying the ticket (300 rupees), to enter and climb up to the top inside. You will see that in the end it is not a real palace, but just a wall with some rooms with small windows. You climb almost to the top, and you can see the view seen by the maharajas wives. Not to be missed.
Visited on
Weekday

Wait time
No wait

Reservation recommended
No
review_translated_text: Il palazzo dei Venti e bellissimo. Costruito per permettere alle mogli della famiglia reale, di poter vedere la strada senza essere viste. Consiglio di non fermarsi solo a fare una fotografia dallesterno, ma oltrepassarlo, e pagare il biglietto (300 rupie), per entrare e salire fino in cima al suo interno. Vedrete che alla fine non e un palazzo vero e proprio, ma solo un muro con alcune stanze con finestrelle. Si sale quasi fino in cima, e si puo vedere il panorama visto dalle mogli del maraja. Da non perdere.

name: SAGAR BHARDWAJ
review_text:
The Hawa Mahal, or Palace of Winds, is an iconic Jaipur landmark that lives up to its reputation. Its intricate facade, adorned with countless windows, is a sight to behold. While the interior is relatively small, it offers a fascinating glimpse into the royal lifestyle.
A word of advice: If youre aiming for that perfect Instagram shot, be prepared to pay a cover charge at the cafes across the road. However, the view of the Hawa Mahal from there is undeniably stunning.
There are basically 2 cafes in front of hawamahal palace that offering great instagram shots but there is entry fee of 200 per person ..if you dont want to spend money u can click from the road but your friend must have great photography skills

name: Aakash Sharma
review_text:
In keeping with the visual language of the "Pink City" of Jaipur, the Hawa Mahal is built entirely in Red Sandstone , which in the sunlight glows with a pink hue. It is often identified as the world's tallest building constructed without a foundation. Hawa Mahal allows the breeze to keep the internal spaces cool explaining the name of the structure which can be translated as "Palace of the Winds." The building, maintained by Rajasthan's archeological department, was renovated in 2006 and is open to tourism.

name: Abdul Kalam
review_text:
Here

Hawa Mahal, the Palace of Winds, is a breathtakingly beautiful monument in Jaipur, India. This 18th-century structure is a testament to the citys rich history and architectural grandeur.

As I approached the palace, I was struck by its stunning facade, adorned with intricate latticework and ornate carvings. The five-story building is designed to resemble a honeycomb, with 953 small windows that allow the wind to circulate, keeping the interior cool.

The palaces architecture is a blend of Hindu and Islamic styles, reflecting the cultural diversity of the region. The interior is equally impressive, with beautifully decorated rooms, corridors, and courtyards.

What I found most fascinating was the palaces history. Built by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh, Hawa Mahal was designed to allow the royal ladies to observe street life without being seen. The small windows and screened balconies provided a glimpse into the outside world while maintaining their seclusion.

The palace is well-maintained, with informative guides available to share its history and significance. The surrounding gardens and courtyards are also worth exploring, offering a peaceful retreat from the bustling city.

Overall, Hawa Mahal is a must-visit attraction in Jaipur. Its stunning architecture, rich history, and cultural significance make it an unforgettable experience.

Tips:

- Best time to visit: Early morning or late afternoon to avoid the crowds
- Wear comfortable shoes for exploring the palace and gardens
- Hire a guide to get the most out of your visit
- Dont miss the stunning views of the city from the top floor

name: Shankar Manju
review_text:
Hawa Mahal popularly known as "Palace of Winds" is one of the finest architecture in Jaipur, Rajasthan. Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh had built this palace in 1799. Hawa Mahal is considered very unique because it has many small windows and balconies which look like a honeycomb [1].

The structure was built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh, grandson of Maharaja Sawai Jai Singh, the founder of Jhunjhunu city in Rajasthan state. [ 2 ] He was so inspired by the unique structure of Khetri Mahal that he built this grand and historical palace.

It was designed by Lal Chand Ustad. Its five-storey outer building resembles a beehive, with 953 small windows called jharokhas decorated with intricate lattice work. [ 3 ] The original intention of the latticed design was to allow royal women to observe everyday life and festivals celebrated on the street below without being seen. This architectural feature also allowed cool air to pass through through the Venturi effect, making the entire area more pleasant during high temperatures in summer. [3] [4] [5] Many people see the Hawa Mahal from the street view and think it is the front part of the palace, but it is the back part. [6]

In 2006, after a gap of 50 years, renovation work was started on the palace to give the monument a facelift, with an estimated cost of Rs 4.568 million. [7] The corporate sector helped preserve the historical monuments of Jaipur and the Unit Trust of India has adopted Hawa Mahal to maintain it. [ 8 ] The palace is an extended part of a huge complex. Stone carved screens, small windows and arched ceilings are some of the features of this popular tourist destination. The monument also has delicately hanging cornices.

name: It's Vaibhav
review_text:
Hawa Mahal, or the Palace of Winds, is one of Jaipurs most iconic landmarks. This five-story structure, made from red and pink sandstone, features 953 small windows that allow cool breezes to pass through, making it a perfect retreat during the summer. The intricate latticework on the windows is a fine example of Rajput architecture. Inside, the palace offers stunning views of the city and the Jantar Mantar observatory. The best time to visit is early in the morning when the sunlight filters through the lattice windows, casting beautiful patterns on the floors.
Recommendation: A must-visit for architecture enthusiasts and those interested in royal history.

name: Sunil Solanki
review_text:
Hawa Mahal, also known as the Palace of Winds, is one of the most iconic landmarks in Jaipur, and my visit there was nothing short of captivating. The first thing that struck me was the stunning facade, an architectural marvel made of pink and red sandstone that stands tall in the heart of the city. The intricate latticework on the 953 small windows, or jharokhas, was mesmerizing, and it was fascinating to learn that these were designed to allow royal women to observe street festivals while remaining unseen.

As I explored the interior, I was taken back by the cool breeze flowing through the palace, which lived up to its name. The design brilliantly maximizes airflow, making the palace remarkably comfortable even on a hot day. The narrow corridors and steep ramps added to the charm, making it feel like a maze of history.

What made the visit even more memorable was the panoramic view from the top, offering a breathtaking glimpse of the bustling city of Jaipur and the surrounding Aravalli Hills. It felt like a perfect blend of history, culture, and natural beauty.

The only downside was that some parts of the palace were a bit crowded, but that's to be expected given its popularity. Overall, visiting Hawa Mahal was a wonderful experience that gave me a deeper appreciation for Jaipurs rich heritage and the architectural brilliance of the bygone era.

name: Vikash Vicky
review_text:
Hawa Mahal, often celebrated for its intricate facade and historical significance, might leave some visitors feeling lukewarm. If youre passionate about history and enjoy exploring historical architecture, this palace in Jaipur is definitely worth a visit. Its unique design and historical context offer a glimpse into Rajasthans regal past.

However, if historical sites arent your primary interest, you might find Hawa Mahal to be somewhat underwhelming. Beyond its exterior beauty, there isnt much to see or do inside, making it a bit of a one-trick pony in the broader spectrum of travel attractions.

name: THE PAGRI SERIES
review_text:
Hawa Mahal famously known as the " palace of winds " has one of the best architecture in Jaipur, Rajasthan. Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh built this palace in 1799. Hawa Mahal is considered to be very unique as it has many small windows and balconies that seem like a honeycomb.

The structure was built in 1799 by the Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh, grandson of Maharaja Sawai Jai Singh, the founder of the city of Jhunjhunu in the state of Rajasthan. He was so inspired by the unique structure of Khetri Mahal that he built this grand and historical palace.

It was designed by Lal Chand Ustad. Its five-floor exterior is akin to a honeycomb with its 953 small windows called Jharokhas decorated with intricate latticework. The original intent of the lattice design was to allow royal ladies to observe everyday life and festivals celebrated in the street below without being seen. This architectural feature also allowed cool air from the Venturi effect to pass through, thus making the whole area more pleasant during the high temperatures in summer. Many people see the Hawa Mahal from the street view and think it is the front of the palace, but it is the back.

In 2006, renovation works on the Mahal were undertaken, after a gap of 50 years, to give a facelift to the monument at an estimated cost of Rs 4.568 million. The corporate sector lent a hand to preserve the historical monuments of Jaipur and the Unit Trust of India has adopted Hawa Mahal to maintain it. The palace is an extended part of a huge complex. The stone-carved screens, small casements, and arched roofs are some of the features of this popular tourist spot. The monument also has delicately modelled hanging cornices.

review_text:
This beautiful and unique architecture is built under the reign of maharaja Sawai pratap singh of Kachhwaha dynasty . Its construction is completed in 1799 It is also known as PALACE OF WINDS , its architect was Lal Chand ustad , its shape is just like a crown (mukhuta) of lord Krishna. It is built from red and pink sandstone , it has around 953 casements or small windows which is called jharokhas in local language , here before queens used to watch TEEZ and GANGAUR procession or sawaris . It has 5 - first floor is SHARAD MANDIR or pratap mandir , second floor is RATAN MANDIR , third floor is VICHITRA MANDIR, fourth floor is PRAKASH MANDIR , fifth and last is HAWA MANDIR . It is on the edge of the city palace jaipur .
In 2006, renovation works on the Mahal were undertaken, after a gap of 50 years.

review_text:
The Hawa Mahal, or Palace of Winds, is an iconic Jaipur landmark that lives up to its reputation. Its intricate facade, adorned with countless windows, is a sight to behold. While the interior is relatively small, it offers a fascinating glimpse into the royal lifestyle.

A word of advice: If youre aiming for that perfect Instagram shot, be prepared to pay a cover charge at the cafes across the road. However, the view of the Hawa Mahal from there is undeniably stunning.

Parking can be a bit of a challenge, especially on weekends. Keep an eye out for blue signboards indicating available parking spots. Theres plenty of street parking, but it might take some patience.

name: Rahul Jain
review_text:
Hawa Mahal, often referred to as the Palace of Winds, is a mesmerizing gem in the heart of Jaipur. Its intricate architecture, characterized by those iconic honeycomb windows, is nothing short of breathtaking. The five-story facade, adorned with 953 small windows or jharokhas, allows a gentle breeze to flow through the palace, making it a cool oasis even in the peak of summer.

The view from inside, looking out through these delicate latticework windows, is simply captivating. Each jharokha offers a unique glimpse of the bustling city below, while simultaneously connecting you to the rich history and vibrant culture of Rajasthan. As you wander through the narrow corridors, you can almost hear the whispers of the past, as if the walls themselves are narrating stories of a bygone era.

Hawa Mahal isnt just a monument; its an experience. If youre passionate about history and architecture, this place is an absolute must-visit. The combination of its architectural beauty and the palpable sense of history that surrounds you makes it a truly unforgettable destination.

name: Abhishek Gurjar
review_text:
HAWA MAHAL...Hawa Mahal, also known as the Palace of Winds, is located in Jaipur, Rajasthan, India. It is located at the edge of the City Palace and extends to the Zenana, or womens chambers.
The five-storey palace was built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh for the court harem. It is known for its magnificent architecture, which blends Hindu Rajput and Islamic Mughal-influenced designs. The palace is famous for its more than 900 windows, which were designed to allow royal women to view the street below without being noticed. The palaces windows showcase colorful glass mosaics and unique craftsmanship, and when sunlight passes through them, the rooms are filled with an iridescent glow.
Hawa Mahal is open every day from 9 am to 5 pm, and visitors can enter at any time during that period. To enter the palace, you must pass through a royal door on the left side of the building, which leads to a large courtyard. There are no stairs inside the palace, so visitors must climb a ramp to reach the top. The top three floors are only one room wide, while the first and second floors face courtyards.
Hawa Mahal is a UNESCO World Heritage Site and one of the most famous buildings in India.

name: Dev Shah
review_text:
I recommend taking a travel guide with you to better understand Hawa Mahal. Also, student entry fees are lower compared to regular rates; students just need to show a photo of their student ID card with its validity.

Avoid buying from shops inside Hawa Mahal as their prices are quite high; the guide may take you there because they receive a commission.

Note: Block-printed shirts available in the market are mostly produced in factories in Ahmedabad and Surat, and are not truly hand-block printed.

Note : Opposite cafe with terrace view of Hawa Mahal with charge you 250/ person, avoiding going there, very rude behaviour of owner, instead click photos from roadside in potrait mode at lower angles.

name: Ruslena Ramli
review_text:
For best pictures head to the Tattoo Cafe across the street and go up to the rooftop. You can choose to enjoy your morning coffee there too and bask in the splendour of Hawa Mahal.

My second trip to Jaipur and trust me when I say it never gets old. The sincerity of its people, the choices of food veg and non-veg is another level, competitive prices and spoiled for choice handblock materials, precious stones, jewelries that cause overweight funny stories when you return home.

Already planning a third trip in 2025

The palace has a fascinating history and offers great views of the city from its upper levels. It's a must-see for anyone interested in Indian architecture and history.

name: Miguel Lobato
review_text:
The very beautiful exterior facade appears on one of the countrys banknotes. But inside it is abandoned. There is no decoration, furniture or lamps, the paint is terrible... Empty rooms with paint half fallen off.
There was a fountain that didnt work... Up on the terrace the floor was like broken plaster and you got stains when you walked.
Come on, like all things in the country... they made it very pretty in photos and then inside it was very messy.
It is not worth entering, and you cannot look out of the facade that faces the street or see through the windows.
With these two photos you see everything there is to see.
PS: Dont even think about stopping to watch the puppet shows even for a minute because first they tell you its free and then they chase you asking for money. I dont know how they allow that in something youve already paid to enter.
Visited on
Weekday

Wait time
No wait

Reservation recommended
No
review_translated_text:
La fachada exterior muy bonita, aparece en uno de los billetes del pais. Pero por dentro esta abandonado. No hay decoracion, mobiliario y ni lamparas, la pintura fatal... Salas vacias con la pintura medio caida.

Habia una fuente que no funcionaba... Encima en la terraza el suelo estaba como de yeso deshecho y te manchas al caminar.

Vamos, como todas las cosas del pais.. te lo ponian muy bonito en fotos y luego por dentro dejadisimo.

No merece la pena entrar, ademas que no te puedes asomar por la fachada que da a la calle ni ver a traves de las ventanas

Con estas dos fotos veis todo lo que hay que ver.

PD: ni se os ocurra pararos a ver los shows de marionetas aunque sea un minuto porque primero os dicen que es gratis y luego os persiguen pidiendo dinero. No se como permiten eso en algo que ya has pagado por entrar

name: Priyanshu Dubey
review_text:
Hawa Mahal, the "Palace of Winds," an architectural marvel in the heart of Jaipur! This stunning five-story palace, built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh, is a brilliant example of Rajputana architecture combined with Mughal influences.

As you approach Hawa Mahal, you'll be captivated by its unique facade, adorned with 953 intricately carved windows, or 'jharokhas.' These tiny windows were designed to allow the royal women to observe the bustling streets below without being seen, ensuring their privacy in line with the traditions of the time.

name: Nikhil Shinde
review_text:
It's one of the famous monuments of Jaipur. During the day you will be mesmerised by its art and architecture during evening you will get stunned by the lighting of the Hawa mahal. There is cafe in front of the Mahal called the tattoo cafe, you can visit the cafe for better view and for capturing some beautiful pictures of yourself. But the cafe charges 250 /- per person for entry which will be deducted from the total bill. Every order takes 25 minutes to arrive. Best time to visit the cafe is after 7PM as Mahal looks great in the night. You can try lassi at the hotel it's nice. We did not like the pizza which ordered. Apart from that there are roadside shops for shopping for men and women both. The mahal is in core of the Johri bazar and near city palace so there are lot of things to do and eat as well.

name: Riyaz Vhora
review_text:
Hawa Mahal, also known as the "Palace of Winds," is a stunning architectural marvel located in Jaipur, India. Built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh, it is a five-story structure made from pink and red sandstone, exemplifying the rich architectural heritage of the Rajput era. Here's a detailed review of the Hawa Mahal:

Architectural Design:

* Facade: The palace's most striking feature is its honeycomb-like facade, consisting of 953 small windows called "jharokhas." These were designed to allow the royal ladies to observe street festivities while remaining unseen, maintaining the traditions of purdah.

Hawa Mahal is a must-visit for history enthusiasts, architecture buffs, and anyone interested in experiencing the cultural heritage of Jaipur. Its unique design, historical relevance, and breathtaking views make it a highlight of any trip to the Pink City.

Must go and visit hawa mahal
