name: Abhishek Singh
review_text:
We visited Hawa Mahal in Jaipur and had an amazing time. You can buy tickets at the entrance or online. Students get a 50% discount if they show their student ID.
Exploring Hawa Mahal was a wonderful experience. The palace has many small windows called jharokhas that let cool air flow through. This design allowed royal ladies to watch the street without being seen. Made of red and pink sandstone, Hawa Mahal combines Rajput and Mughal architectural styles. It was built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh and is designed to look like the crown of Krishna, a Hindu god. Inside, there are beautiful courtyards, passages, and arched roofs, making it perfect for photos.
The best part was the view from the top of Hawa Mahal. You can see all of Jaipur, and it looks incredible.
Our visit to Hawa Mahal was fantastic. Buying tickets was easy, and students get a good discount. The palace's design and history are fascinating. The view from the top is breathtaking, showing the whole city of Jaipur. Hawa Mahal is a must-visit for its beauty and historical importance. Dont miss it when youre in Jaipur!

name: Deewanshi vyas
review_text:
I recently visited the Hawa Mahal in Jaipur, and I was left spellbound by its ethereal beauty and intricate architecture. This 18th-century palace is a masterpiece of Rajput design, and its sheer scale and grandeur took my breath away.

As I approached the palace, I was struck by its distinctive pink sandstone facade, adorned with intricate latticework and ornate carvings. The palaces unique five-story design, with its 953 small windows, is a marvel of engineering and craftsmanship.

Inside, I discovered a tranquil oasis, with cool breezes whispering through the corridors and chambers. The palaces ingenious design allows for maximum ventilation, making it a haven from the desert heat.

What I loved most about Hawa Mahal was its rich history and cultural significance. Built for the royal ladies to observe street life without being seen, it offers a fascinating glimpse into the lives of Jaipurs former rulers.

_Highlights:_

- Breathtaking architecture and intricate carvings
- Unique design and ventilation system
- Rich history and cultural significance
- Stunning views of the surrounding city
- Peaceful and serene atmosphere

_Tips:_

- Visit early in the morning or late in the evening to avoid the crowds
- Take a guided tour to uncover the palaces hidden secrets and stories
- Dont miss the nearby City Palace and Jantar Mantar for a comprehensive experience

Overall, Hawa Mahal is an unforgettable experience that will leave you enchanted by its beauty, history, and cultural significance. A must-visit destination in Jaipur!

name: Saif Ali Quadri
review_text:
Hawa Mahal, located in Jaipur, India, is an architectural marvel that exemplifies Rajputana architecture with its intricate lattice work and 953 small windows, or jharokhas, which were originally designed to allow royal ladies to observe everyday life and festivities in the street below while remaining unseen. Built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh, it stands as a symbol of Jaipurs rich cultural heritage and is a must-visit for history enthusiasts and architecture lovers alike.

review_text:
Hawa Mahal was built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh, this five-story palace is known for its beautiful pink and red sandstone exterior with 953 small windows, or jharokhas. These windows allowed royal women to watch street festivals without being seen and kept the palace cool.

The architecture is a mix of Rajput and Mughal styles, featuring detailed latticework, small domes, and pillars. Inside, the palace is simpler, but it offers amazing views of Jaipurs busy streets and the Aravalli hills from the upper floors.

name: Akash K
review_text:
Hawa Mahal, also known as the Palace of Winds, is one of the most iconic landmarks in Jaipur, India. Built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh, it holds immense historical significance. The structure was designed by Lal Chand Ustad and stands as a testament to the rich cultural and architectural heritage of the Rajput era. Hawa Mahal is a symbol of the royal lineage and the grandeur of the Kachwaha Rajputs who ruled Jaipur.

Architecture:

Hawa Mahal is a five-story structure that resembles the honeycomb of a beehive. It is built in the shape of Lord Krishnas crown, reflecting Maharaja Pratap Singhs devotion to the Hindu god. The facade is made from red and pink sandstone, typical of the architecture found in Jaipur. The Mahal is adorned with intricate latticework, finials, and domed canopies, all of which exemplify the Rajput architectural style.

Builder:

The palace was constructed under the patronage of Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh, the ruler of Jaipur from 1778 to 1803. The chief architect was Lal Chand Ustad, who meticulously designed the structure to meet the aesthetic and functional requirements of the era.

Significance of the Windows and Colored Glasses:

Hawa Mahal boasts 953 small windows, known as jharokhas, decorated with intricate latticework. These windows were not merely ornamental; they served a practical purpose. The lattice allowed royal ladies to observe daily life and festivals in the street below without being seen, adhering to the strict purdah system of the time. The design also facilitated the circulation of cool air, making the entire structure air-conditioned in the hot desert climate.

The colored glasses on the windows added to the aesthetic appeal of the palace. When sunlight filters through these glasses, it creates a stunning display of colors inside the Mahal, enhancing its beauty and providing a cooling effect:

Purpose of Construction:

Hawa Mahal was built to provide the royal women a place to observe everyday street life and festivals without being seen by the public. This was crucial due to the purdah system that required royal women to remain unseen by strangers. Additionally, the structure was meant to enhance the cooling effect through its unique architectural design, which made it an early example of climate-responsive architecture.

Hawa Mahal is not just an architectural marvel but also a symbol of Jaipur's royal heritage. Its historical importance, unique design, and functional elegance make it a must-visit for anyone interested in the rich cultural history of Rajasthan. The palace continues to enchant visitors with its beauty and historical significance, standing as a proud reminder of the ingenuity of its creators.

name: Kaushal Kumar
review_text:
Hawa Mahal, the Palace of Winds, is an iconic masterpiece in the heart of Jaipur! This stunning architectural wonder is a testament to the citys rich history and cultural heritage. As I approached the palace, I was struck by its sheer size and intricate design.

The palaces unique architecture, with its 953 windows and ornate facade, is a marvel of Rajput engineering. The attention to detail and craftsmanship are evident in every aspect of the building, from the delicate latticework to the beautifully painted motifs.

As I explored the palace, I was impressed by the clever use of natural ventilation, which keeps the interior cool even in the scorching desert heat. The views from the top floors are breathtaking, offering a panoramic view of the city and the surrounding hills.

Hawa Mahal is not just a beautiful building; its a symbol of the citys rich history and cultural heritage. Its a must-visit destination for anyone interested in architecture, history, or simply experiencing the beauty of Jaipur. Dont miss out on the chance to be awed by this incredible palace!

name: Nishant Birman
review_text:
We just went for the photo opportunity. Lots of great shots. Cross the street for another view. Can go to the restaurant across the street for better shots. The best part of This area is the cheap jewelry shops. Great bangles and even a guy sitting on a blanket selling gem rings for 100r. Lots of earrings and gifts to buy. I did buy two cotton pants and they bust the seam the second I sat down so maybe try on first.
Hawa mahal is one of the known attraction when u visit Jaipur. Its a walk way place for 1 to cover when visiting City palace & jantar Mantar. You can take photo with Hawa mahal & move onto your next attraction. The same can also b seen within your travel from road to amber fort.

In the heart of Jaipur, Hawa Mahal stands not just as a historical relic but as a living testament to the artistic and architectural brilliance of its era. The palace offers mesmerizing views, both from the top and the front, where you can see the forts around the city. The interior of the palace is beautifully decorated with paintings and intricate carvings. The many windows, constructed for the queens to look from, are a significant attraction. The palace is well-lit at night, offering a different perspective of its beauty. Inside the palace, there is a museum that provides insights into the rich history of Jaipur and the Mahal itself. The palace has two parts, Badi Chaupad and Choti Chaupad, but visitors are not allowed inside these areas. Hawa Mahal is located in a crowded part of Jaipur, but it is easily accessible. Bapu Bazar is within walking distance. Its recommended to visit Hawa Mahal early in the morning, ideally reaching by 9:00 AM, to witness a beautiful reflection of the sun through the colourful glasses. It is open from 9 AM to 4:30 PM. The palace is well-maintained by the authorities, which is commendable. The entry fee for Indians is Rs. 50, while for foreigners, its Rs. 200. To fully explore the place, you would need approximately 2 hours. Dont forget to bring camera, as there are fantastic photo opportunities in and around the Mahal. It is surrounded by shops and restaurants, making it a perfect place for a leisurely stroll or a quick meal.
Hawa Mahal is another great architecture and one of the main attractions of Jaipur. Hawa Mahal has a no of windows so that wind can be passed through those windows.The view from outside is different in the morning and evening. Ill suggest something between 5-6 so, you can see both the views. Hawa Mahal is an open area behind a wall which was meant for the ladies in the palace to see the activities going on in the city. The wall contains 900+ small windows with colourful glasses You can click pictures here from outside without giving any money or take a ticket for 52/-(Indian) and visit from inside as well.
Even a short visit is worthwhile, I think. Parking is the biggest hassle- our bus went before 8.30, so as to park nearby, as its a regular street otherwise, so limited parking spots. Its the beauty of the building that makes it worth seeing. Learn its history, and appreciate the viewing. Its stunning.
.This place is very quite nice and amazing. Any buddy will be making any vlogs and photography. Here will be you not facing any problem for any buddy from outside India. But it not have any wheelchair or wheelchair service at here. And also too for solo travelers.

name: ADV. SANDEEP GAUTAM
review_text:
Hawa Mahal is a famous palace located in Jaipur, Rajasthan. It is also called Pawan Mahal or City Palace.
This palace was built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh II. It is made of red and pink sandstone and its architecture is a mix of Mughal and Rajput styles.
Hawa Mahal is known for its unique architecture. It has 5 floors and has 953 small windows. Due to these windows, air flow is maintained in the palace, due to which the palace remains cool even during the summer season.
Hawa Mahal is one of the most popular tourist destinations in Jaipur. It is located in the center of the city and opposite Badi Chaupar Chowk.

* Hawa Mahal is also called the crown of the city.
* This palace was one of the favorite places of Maharaja Jai   Singh II.
* Hawa Mahal has many rooms, including Sheesh Mahal, Harem and Baradari.
* A panoramic view of Jaipur city is visible from the rooftop of Hawa Mahal.
* Hawa Mahal is visited by millions of tourists every year.
Here are some tips for visiting Hawa Mahal:
* Hawa Mahal is open from 9 am to 6 pm.
*Entry fee is 50.
* To reach Hawa Mahal you can take auto rickshaw, bus or taxi.
* There are many restaurants and shops near Hawa Mahal.
* If you are traveling to Jaipur, do visit Hawa Mahal.

name: Ansh Gupta Physio
review_text:
Go with your college Id card and get tickets only 22 INR per student.
The Hawa Mahal, also known as the Palace of Winds, is a stunning five-story palace located in Jaipur, India. Constructed from red and pink sandstone, its famed for its unique facade resembling a honeycomb. The facade is adorned with 953 intricately latticed windows, called jharokhas, allowing cool breezes to flow through the palace during the hot summers. Built in 1799, the Hawa Mahal served as an extension to the City Palaces womens chambers, enabling the royal ladies to observe street life while maintaining privacy.

name: Yogesh Ram
review_text: The Hawa Mahal is a five-storey building, and it is the tallest building in the world that has been built without a foundation. It has a curved architecture that leans at an 87 degree angle, and a pyramidal shape which has helped it stay erect for centuries. The Hawa Mahal is dedicated to Lord Krishna. The Hawa Mahal was built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh. He was the grandson of Maharaja Sawai Jai Singh, who was the founder of Jaipur.

name: Devendrapratap Singh
review_text:
one of the most beautiful place in jaipur .Hawa Mahal is a palace in the city of Jaipur, India. Built from red and pink sandstone, the palace sits on the edge of the City Palace, Jaipur, and extends to the Zenana, or womens chambers. The entry to the Hawa Mahal from the city palace side is through an imperial door. It opens into a large courtyard, which has double-storeyed buildings on three sides, with the Hawa Mahal enclosing it on the east side. An archaeological museum is also housed in this courtyard..

name: Farhan Qureshi
review_text:
Jaipurs Hawa Mahal, or Palace of the Winds, is a stunning five-story structure famous for its pink sandstone facade and 953 intricately latticed windows. Built in the 1700s, it was designed for the royal women to observe street life while remaining unseen. The facade resembles a honeycomb, and cool breezes flow through the many windows, providing natural air conditioning.

The experience of exploring its multiple levels and intricate windows left me in awe. I highly recommend visiting Hawa Mahal to anyone interested in history, culture, and architecture.

name: AVTAR SINGH MAHECHA
review_text:
Rajasthan is a place of royals and many wonders, and Hawa Mahal is one such gem. It's not just the architecture, Hawa Mahal's history and facts will let you view this structure in a new light. Of course, it's one of the iconic landmarks of Jaipur, and is famed for its pink latticed balconies and windows that offer breathtaking views of the city.

Also known as the Palace of the Winds, it's one of the finest examples of Rajput architecture in the country, and was built in 1799 by the Kachwaha ruler of Jaipur Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh as an extension to the Royal City Palace.

name: Rahul Dhaker
review_text:
The Hawa Mahal is a palace in the city of Jaipur, Rajasthan, India. Built from red and pink sandstone, it is on the edge of the City Palace, Jaipur, and extends to the Zenana, or womens chambers.
The structure was built in 1799 by the Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh, grandson of Maharaja Sawai Jai Singh, the founder of the city of Jhunjhunu in the state of Rajasthan. He was so inspired by the unique structure of Khetri Mahal that he built this grand and historical palace.
It was designed by Lal Chand Ustad. Its five-floor exterior is akin to a honeycomb with its 953 small windows called Jharokhas decorated with intricate latticework. The original intent of the lattice design was to allow royal ladies to observe everyday life and festivals celebrated in the street below without being seen. This architectural feature also allowed cool air from the Venturi effect to pass through, thus making the whole area more pleasant during the high temperatures in summer. Many people see the Hawa Mahal from the street view and think it is the front of the palace, but it is the back.
In 2006, renovation works on the Mahal were undertaken, after a gap of 50 years, to give a facelift to the monument at an estimated cost of Rs 4.568 million. The corporate sector lent a hand to preserve the historical monuments of Jaipur and the Unit Trust of India has adopted Hawa Mahal to maintain it. The palace is an extended part of a huge complex. The stone-carved screens, small casements, and arched roofs are some of the features of this popular tourist spot. The monument also has delicately modeled hanging cornices.

Hawa Mahal of Jaipur is associated with Lord Shri Krishna. However, it was built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh, the Kachwaha ruler of Jaipur, who was a great devotee of Shri Krishna. This is the reason why he gave this palace the form of the crown of Shri Krishna. Today this palace is one of the most attractive tourist places of Jaipur. It is a five-storey building, which is tilted at an angle of 87 degrees due to lack of solid foundation.

Like the name of Hawa Mahal, its structure is also amazing. This five-storey building was designed by Lal Chand Ustad. Tourists use a ramp to reach the topmost part of Hawa Mahal. The interesting thing is that there are 953 small windows in this palace, which are called Jharoka. Beautiful carvings have been done on these very minutely. The reason for making them was also very special. Actually, the women of the royal family were not allowed to leave the house.
In such a situation, she used to watch the programs and plays happening on the streets through these windows only. These windows were made with great care so that women did not face any inconvenience in seeing the outside. Let us tell you that at that time there was the practice of purdah. According to this rule, women had to keep their faces covered. She could not show her face to anyone even by mistake.
An interesting thing about this palace is that the entry into this palace is not from the front but from the back door. There is a grand door at the rear of the palace, through which tourists enter inside the palace. The highest part of Hawa Mahal can be visited. From here you can see Jantar Mantar, City Palace and Sir Deori Bazaar very well. There is also a museum inside the palace, where a collection of historical things can be seen. Next time you visit the Pink City of Jaipur, do not forget to explore Hawa Mahal.

Weekday

Reservation recommended

The palace looks stunning when lit up at night, making it a sight not to be missed.

name: Delhi Fun Dos
review_text:
Visiting Hawa Mahal, also known as the Palace of Winds, was a highlight of our recent trip to Jaipur. This iconic red sandstone structure stands tall as a symbol of the city, with its intricate facade featuring 953 jharokhas or windows, designed to allow royal women to observe street festivities while maintaining their privacy. Despite the scorching April heat outside, the interior of Hawa Mahal remained remarkably cool, a testament to its ingenious architectural design. The palaces labyrinthine layout and ornate Rajasthani decor, including stuccoed walls and colourful stained-glass windows, offered a glimpse into the rich cultural heritage of Rajasthan. Climbing to the upper floors provided panoramic views of Jaipurs bustling streets and stunning sunsets, making it a must-visit for both history enthusiasts and photographers alike.
Exploring Hawa Mahal Inside, the palace complex revealed a blend of historical charm and functional spaces, now repurposed as ticket counters, souvenir shops, and photo booths. The central courtyard with its intermittent fountain added a tranquil touch amidst the palaces vibrant ambiance. Visitors can also enjoy Rajasthani puppet shows and explore exhibits of ancient statues and artifacts, offering deeper insights into the regions cultural legacy. Whether admiring the palaces ornate details or soaking in the panoramic views from its highest points, Hawa Mahal promises an unforgettable experience that encapsulates the essence of Jaipurs architectural marvels and cultural splendor.

name: Chandan Brahman
review_text:
Best palace and Incredible experience
Jaipur is the capital of Rajasthan and its beauty and historical importance really fascinated me. The citys deep historical heritage, Rajasthani-style gardens and the lively atmosphere of the markets make it a unique and memorable place.

With its ancient citadels and palaces, the city has a unique aspect of life and culture. Havelis have their specialty in architecture and reflect the beauty of the traditional architecture of Rajasthan. Jaipur is famous as the Pink City for its beautiful palaces and thriving economy.

Despite this, Jaipur continues to strive to keep its important historical traditions alive even with its modernization. The Rajasthani kitchen and special food here also becomes a part of the imaginative experience of the city.

Ultimately, Jaipur is one of the beautiful cities in the world, of which every Indian can be proud.

name: mayank bhatnagar
review_text:
Hawa Mahal: A Stunning Facade with a Royal Past

The Hawa Mahal, or Palace of Winds, is a must-see in Jaipur. Its iconic pink sandstone facade, adorned with hundreds of tiny windows, is a dazzling example of Rajput architecture. While the interior is fairly small, the views from the top and the historical significance make it worthwhile.

Highlights:

Stunning pink sandstone facade with intricate details

Offers a glimpse into royal life and ingenious cooling system design
Beautiful at sunrise and sunset with the changing light

Things to Consider:

The interior is small and doesnt take long to explore
Can get crowded, especially during peak season.

Overall, Hawa Mahal is a beautiful and unique landmark thats definitely worth adding to your Jaipur itinerary.

review_text:
by waris khan
Hawa Mahal, Jaipur - Jewel of Rajasthani Style

Hawa Mahal is located in Jaipur, the capital of Rajasthan and is a major tourist destination. It is famous for its unique architecture and air-duct ventilation. Hawa Mahal was built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh.

Its specialty is that despite being a small palace, it is known for its 953 windows and latticed windows. From here you can see a unique view of the ancient Rajasthani life of the old city of Jaipur.

Hawa Mahal is a must visit place for tourists visiting Jaipur. It is very famous for its beauty and as a symbol of Rajasthani heritage.

name: Mahendra Choudhary
review_text:
Title: Breathtaking night view at Hawa Mahal, Jaipur

I recently had the opportunity to visit the iconic Hawa Mahal in the evening in Jaipur, and the experience was nothing short of magical. The stunning architecture of this historical monument comes alive under the magical glow of night lights, creating a truly mesmerizing sight that left me in awe.

As I stood in front of the intricately designed facade of Hawa Mahal, I was amazed to see the intricate lattice work and countless windows letting in the cool evening breeze. The play of light and shadow on the sandstone walls gave the structure a mystical aura that took me back to the royal era of Rajasthan.

The vibrant atmosphere around Hawa Mahal further added to the charm of the visit, with street vendors selling local snacks and souvenirs and crowds of visitors enjoying the beauty of the monument. The upper floors of Hawa Mahal offer a panoramic view of the city of Jaipur, lit up with twinkling lights, a moment I will always remember.

Overall, the night visit to Hawa Mahal was a pleasant experience full of history, culture and natural beauty. I highly recommend this fascinating place to anyone visiting Jaipur, especially in the evening when the monument really shines in its full glory.

In the end, my visit to Hawa Mahal under the night sky was a memorable and breathtaking experience that exceeded all my expectations. It is a must-see destination for anyone wishing to explore the vibrant heritage and architectural wonders of Jaipur.

name: Roshan Jha
review_text:
Hawa Mahal, or the Palace of Winds, is a stunning palace in Jaipur, India. built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh. Its famous for its 953 small windows, which allow cool air to flow through the palace, keeping it comfortable even in the heat. These windows also let royal women observe street festivals without being seen. Ticket charges for Indians are Rs 52.
My personal view
Nowadays, it offers a mixed experience for tourists, not that much attractive,The best time to visit is from February to March and September to November.

This palace has around 900 windows. So hawa will be coming all the time. So it is known as Hawa Mahal. This is also known as the Ladies palace. Royal Ladies used to see the city through these windows.

name: MD TAUSIF RAZA
review_text:
I recently visited Hawa Mahal in Jaipur, and it was an incredible experience that left a lasting impression. The architecture of this historic monument is nothing short of breathtaking. Built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh, the Hawa Mahal, or Palace of Winds, stands as a testament to the extraordinary craftsmanship of the workers from that era.The most striking feature of Hawa Mahal is its unique facade, which resembles a honeycomb with its 953 small windows, or jharokhas. These windows were designed to allow the royal ladies to observe everyday life and festivals on the streets below without being seen, adhering to the strict purdah system of that time. The intricate latticework also allows a cool breeze to pass through, providing natural air conditioning within the palace, which is especially refreshing during the hot summer months.Walking through the corridors of Hawa Mahal, I was amazed by the detailed and delicate architecture. The red and pink sandstone structure stands five stories high and offers a panoramic view of the city from the top. Each floor has its own unique charm and offers a glimpse into the regal history of Jaipur.One of the highlights of my visit was the stunning views of the Jantar Mantar and City Palace from the windows of Hawa Mahal. The experience of seeing Jaipur from this vantage point is truly magical and provides a deeper appreciation of the citys rich heritage.For those interested in photography, Hawa Mahal offers numerous opportunities to capture its beauty from different angles. The play of light and shadow through the jharokhas creates mesmerizing patterns, making it a photographers paradise.
Visited on
Weekend

name: ANURAG JADAUN
review_text: Palace of Winds The history of Hawa Mahal is quite interesting. It was built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh, the Kachhwaha Rajput of Jaipur, for the court harem so that they could watch royal processions and street life. The exquisite pink and red sandstone Mahal is known for its attractive architecture, and the beautiful Jhali work on its 953 windows.

name: Manoj Jat
review_text: The Hawa Mahal, or Palace of Winds, is an architectural marvel located in Jaipur, India. Its intricate facade adorned with 953 small windows, or jharokhas, makes it a stunning sight to behold. While its a historical landmark, its more of an ornamental facade rather than a substantial palace. Nonetheless, its unique design and historical significance make it a must-visit for anyone exploring Jaipurs rich cultural heritage.

name: Ankur Kumar
review_text:
Hawa Mahal is a historic palace in Jaipur, India, known for its intricate facade with hundreds of small windows. Built in 1799, it allowed royal women to observe street life without being seen due to the purdah system. Its a symbol of Jaipurs rich heritage and architectural beauty. Hawa Mahal is not just a tourist attraction but also holds cultural significance for the people of Jaipur and Rajasthan, serving as a symbol of the citys rich heritage and architectural prowess. There is also a cafeteria inside the premises. Washrooms and drinking water are also available.

name: Satyam Shivam 2608
review_text:
Hawa Mahal, palace in the Indian city of Jaipur that was designed by Lal Chand Ustad for Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh, the grandson of the founder of Jaipur, and was completed in 1799. Regarded as one of the iconic symbols of the state of Rajasthan, it sits in the center of Rajasthan's capital city.

Built as an extension to the women's chambers of the City Palace, Hawa Mahal was intended as a viewing screen. Through this screen--a kind of architectural veil--women of the royal household could freely view the bazaar and its vibrant proceedings unseen. The term mahal in this context is almost misleading, as the building was never meant to serve as a residence. The five-story building is actually quite shallow, with the top three stories being barely a room deep and containing chambers in which the women sat.

name: SHUBHAM GAUR
review_text:
The Hawa Mahal is a palace in the city of Jaipur, Rajasthan, India. Built from red and pink sandstone, it is on the edge of the City Palace, Jaipur, and extends to the Zenana, or womens chambers.
Hawa Mahal means 'Palace of Winds' or 'Pawan Mahal'. It has 953 small windows (Jharokhas), and they were built to control the air inside the palace. In olden times it was a summer retreat for many Rajput families.

You can imagine any building without a foundation. No problem, just look at Hawa Mahal. Yes, Hawa Mahal stands proudly without a foundation and it is also considered to be one of the tallest buildings in the world without any foundation.

name: Skanda N
review_text:
A must visit in Jaipur. Youll get to explore whole palace / mahal. The best time I would suggest to visit is after 3 30 PM. Because, as the name suggests, the palace will be bit cooler as the circulation of wind is quite good. Exploring the whole palace would take 2 hours. After that come outside and experience the beauty of palace in evening when the palace is illuminated by light

name: Nozomi Okamoto
review_text:
Its an interesting building.
The entrance was hard to find, so I found a small sign on the right side of the building and went inside.
Once inside, follow the path and youll find another entrance. (left)
There will be people performing music and puppetry inside, and they will ask for donations, so its a good idea to bring some change. I didnt have any rupee change so I ignored it.

name: Santosh Singh
review_text:
Hawa Mahal is a true testament to the Jaipur's rich cultural heritage and architectural brilliance. Made of red and pink sandstone, this palace of unusual architecture is a stunning example of local artistry.
For the ultimate Hawa Mahal experience, a visit to the Tattoo cafe is an absolute must. The cafe's strategic location offers visitors a unique perspective of Hawa Mahal.

name: Prabhat Ji
review_text:
Hawa Mahal is a royal palace in Jaipur, the capital of the Indian state of Rajasthan. It was built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh near the metro station at Rajasthan Jaipur Badi Chaupar and was designed by architect Lal Chand Ustad like a rajmukut. This is very good, please watch it and then give your review.

name: pagl pnti c2
review_text:
The Hawa Mahal, also known as the Palace of the Winds, is located in the Indian city of Jaipur. Completed in 1799 and now a UNESCO World Heritage Site, its one of Indias most recognizable buildings and a popular tourist attraction.

It was designed by Lal Chand Ustad. Its five-floor exterior is akin to a honeycomb with its 953 small windows called Jharokhas.

*PALACE OF WINDS*
Hindi :-
Hawa Mahal, also known as the Palace of the Winds, is located in the city of Jaipur, India. Completed in 1799 and now a UNESCO World Heritage Site, it is one of Indias most recognizable buildings and a popular tourist attraction.
It was designed by Lal Chand Ustad. Its five-story exterior is shaped like a beehive, with 953 small windows, called jharokhas,

name: Pokarram Parihar
review_text:
Where is Hawa Mahal?
One of the iconic sites of Jaipur is Hawa Mahal, which is famous for its pink latticed windows. This historical heritage is present in the old part of the city, after seeing which you will just keep staring at it for a few minutes. As the name suggests, this historical heritage known as the Palace of Winds has many stories stored within it, with the help of whose windows we will try to peek into them.

When was Hawa Mahal built?
Hawa Mahal was built in 1799 by the Kachwaha ruler of Jaipur, Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh, as an extension of the Royal City Palace. Today it is one of the most popular tourist attractions of the city. Let us know everything about this monument.
What is the specialty of Hawa Mahal?
The five-storey Hawa Mahal boasts of a rich exterior, which, according to records, was designed by Lal Chand Ustad in the shape of the crown of Lord Krishna. Tourists can use the ramp to reach the topmost part of Hawa Mahal. The most fascinating interesting thing about this monument is that it has 953 small windows with intricate carvings. These small windows are also called Jharokha.
When it was constructed years ago, the reason behind it was that it served as a summer retreat for many Rajput families. It was designed in such a way that air would flow through it, providing relief to the residents during summers.

What is the idea behind building Hawa Mahal?
According to existing records, the basic intention behind the design of this structure was that the ladies of the royal court, who could not go out, could watch the drama taking place on the streets from here. The windows of the palace were carefully designed so that the women could enjoy every view from behind the window lattices. According to the strict rules of purdah of that time, women had to keep their faces covered and could not show their faces in public.

What are the other attractions of Hawa Mahal?
A large and grand door has been built behind this building, through which one can enter the Hawa Mahal from inside the palace because there is no entry way from the front. By going to the topmost part of Hawa Mahal, you get to see many more beautiful views, like Jantar Mantar, Sir Deori Bazaar and City Palace. Apart from this, there is also a small museum inside Hawa Mahal, in which you will get to see many historical things.
Visited on
Weekday

Wait time
Up to 10 min

Reservation recommended
Yes

name: The Jaatregiment
review_text:
Hawa Mahal, or the Palace of Winds, in Jaipur is an architectural gem that leaves visitors spellbound. Its stunning facade, adorned with intricate lattice-worked windows, creates a mesmerizing play of light and air. The palaces purpose becomes evident as you step inside and feel the gentle breeze that flows through the honeycomb-like structure. The historical significance of Hawa Mahal, built as an extension of the City Palace, adds to its allure. The panoramic views from its numerous balconies provide a glimpse into the bustling streets of Jaipur. A visit to this iconic landmark is a must for those seeking a glimpse into Rajasthans rich history and architectural grandeur....

Pink City Jaipur Rangila Rajsthan....

review_text:
One of the iconic heritage marvel that attracts the tourists instantly. It is only a privilege for us today to see such an excellent engineering keeping in mind all the needs of people then.

The royal feeling that you experience while gazing out from the windows, the cool corridors that have been crafted so intelligently to keep away the strong heat, the intricate work on the panels and ceilings and the beautiful use of vibrant coloured glasses instantly makes you feel the magnificence.

Would recommend all not just to click the pictures from outside but visiting and exploring each corner inside Would surely take you back in time to experience the fabulous possessions we can explore

name: Yogesh Kumar Sisodiya
review_text:
HAWAMAHAL, A Must-Visit Gem

The Hawa Mahal in Jaipur is a captivating architectural wonder. Its intricate honeycomb design and delicate latticework allow gentle breezes to flow through, offering respite from the desert heat. Inside, ornate chambers and vibrant murals speak of royal opulence.

The strategic layout provides panoramic views of Jaipurs bustling streets. The onsite museum preserves Rajasthans rich heritage, offering insight into the palaces history. Standing atop its terraces at sunset offers an ethereal experience, leaving visitors spellbound.

In short, a visit to Hawa Mahal is a journey through history and an unforgettable adventure for anyone captivated by beauty and grandeur.

review_text:

This was such a fascinating place to visit. This is also known as the Palace of the Winds. The whole city of Jaipur is so beautiful it is known as the Pink City. A lot of the buildings & city walls are Pink, & they were painted Pink for a visit of Prince Albert

name: Manish Kumar Jha
review_text:
This place boasts excellent visibility and is effortlessly found, making it a social hotspot.
The nearby cafe across the lane provides a picturesque backdrop for capturing memories.
Additionally, there are plenty of good dining options in the vicinity, adding to the appeal.
However, the experience is marred by frequent traffic jams and the absence of adequate parking facilities.
Despite its charms, navigating through the congested roads and struggling to find a parking spot can be a frustrating ordeal.
Visitors may find themselves spending more time stuck in traffic than enjoying the amenities the area has to offer.
While the atmosphere and dining choices are commendable, the inconvenience caused by the traffic and parking situation may deter some from fully appreciating all that this location has to offer.

Overall, while it has its perks, the constant battle with traffic and parking can dampen the overall experience for those looking to enjoy a hassle-free outing.
